</preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/7003945037</author-url><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60027950" id="60027950"/></author></dc:creator><dc:description><abstract original="y" xml:lang="eng">
<ce:para>Chlorinated solvents and other recalcitrant toxicants degrade groundwater quality and threaten human health. Permanent treatment of contaminated groundwater plumes requires that the source of contamination be addressed. For chlorinated solvents, this source is typically a neat oil phase present as a Dense Non-Aqueous Phase Liquid, or DNAPL. In many cases the depth of the DNAPL contamination precludes ex situ treatment alternatives, and there are few viable in situ options for locating and degrading subsurface DNAPL. To be effective, in situ DNAPL remedial agents should provide rapid degradation, produce only non-toxic reaction products, be easily applied in saturated or unsaturated porous media, have the ability to target the DNAPL source zone, and not pose any potential health concerns of its own. Leveraging recent advances in nanotechnology and cross-disciplinary expertise from several engineering and science disciplines, we have designed and synthesized reactive zerovalent iron nanoparticles with unique surface properties that enables them to be readily delivered through water-saturated porous media to subsurface DNAPL in situ, and to localize at the DNAPL/water interface where they can rapidly and efficiently degrade trichloroethylene (TCE) to non-toxic products. The development and evaluation of these novel particles will be described including i) the nanoiron -promoted reduction of TCE and the effect of polymeric coatings on their reactivity, ii) the rapid aggregation of nanoiron due to their magnetic properties, iii) the efficacy of several potential polymeric surface modifiers on mobility in water-saturated porous media, and iv) the geochemical effects on polymer-modified nanoiron mobility in water saturated porous media.</ce:para>
